): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."],"variants":[{"name":"McGreevy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Seamus, Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Riabhaigh</b>, a patronymic from the personal name <i>Riabhach</i> ‘brindled, grizzled’. Compare   Reavey   and   Creevy   2."]},{"name":"Grayer","meanings":["English (southern): nickname from Middle English <i>grei</i> ‘gray’ (see   Gray  ) + <i>her</i> ‘hair’.","Scottish (Ayrshire): variant of   Greer  ."]},{"name":"Grays","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Gray  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, or of   Grace  ."]},{"name":"Grice","meanings":["English (Midlands): from Middle English <i>grice</i>, <i>grise</i> ‘pig’ (Old Norse <i>gríss</i>), probably a nickname or a metonymic occupational name for a swineherd.","English: nickname for a gray-haired man, from Middle English <i>grice</i>, <i>gris</i> ‘gray’ (Old French <i>gris</i>, apparently of ancient Germanic origin, and probably a distant cognate of   Gray   1).","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Greis  ."]},{"name":"Grey","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: variant of   Gray  .","German: dialect variant of   Grau  .","In some cases also an American shortened and altered form of Ukrainian <b>Grushko</b>: nickname or topographic name derived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."]}]},{"name":"MARGARET","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"MARGARET GRAY was born about 1395, in Clayton, Lancashire, England. She had at least 1 son with John de Ashton. She died in 1434, in her hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"about 1395–1434":"umbes 1395–1434","1342–1428":"1342–1428","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1395–1434":"1395–1434","3 September 1428":"3. september 1428","1434":"1434","1421":"1421","1486":"1486","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1428":"1428","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England":"Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1395–1434":"noin 1395–1434","1342–1428":"1342–1428","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1395–1434":"1395–1434","3 September 1428":"3. syyskuuta 1428","1434":"1434","1421":"1421","1486":"1486","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1428":"1428","about 1395":"noin 1395","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, England","Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England":"Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1395–1434":"environ 1395–1434","1342–1428":"1342–1428","1421–1486":"1421–1486","1395–1434":"1395–1434","3 September 1428":"3 septembre 1428","1434":"1434","1421":"1421","1486":"1486","1342":"1342","1395":"1395","1428":"1428","about 1395":"environ 1395","Clayton, Lancashire, England":"Clayton, Lancashire, Angleterre","Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, England":"Ashton-under-Lyne, Lancashire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"MARGARET GRAY est née environ 1395, à Clayton, Lancashire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec John de Ashton. Elle est décédée en 1434, dans sa vil